# **Abstract**

Modern piped water infrastructure relies on electricity to distribute and treat drinking water and wastewater. In the event of catastrophic infrastructure loss caused by a high-altitude electromagnetic pulse, geomagnetic storm, coordinated cyber attack, or extreme pandemic-induced labor shortages, the loss of power could cause a collapse of water systems, potentially putting billions at risk of losing water access. In this study, we estimate the percentage of populations able to access a freshwater source by walking or cycling in such a catastrophe. We combine kinesiology models of walking (Lankford) and cycling (Martin) with a high-resolution global spatial analysis, using data on population density, repeated across 1000 Monte Carlo simulations while accounting for distance to water, slope, road type, piped water access, and bicycle ownership to run a high-resolution global spatial analysis of water access. In order to account for high-uncertainty variables, we repeat this analysis across 1000 Monte Carlo simulations while varying walking energy expenditure, cycling power output, hours collecting water, rolling resistance, and Euclidean detour index. Our results indicate that 24.3% (90% CI 14.4-34.8%) of the world’s population would be unable to access freshwater in an infrastructure loss catastrophe — 28.2% would from be able to reach water by walking, 12.0% by cycling, and 35.6% by using an existing unpiped source. Under these circumstances, cycling could enable access for 12.0% of people, allowing those with bicycles to reach sources too far to walk to. We tie these findings to real-world evidence of water systems collapsing from electricity blackouts in Venezuela, and explore options to build resilience for future infrastructure loss events. Given the vast populations that could be affected, these results highlight the importance of conducting national risk assessments of water access in catastrophic infrastructure loss scenarios and using these to inform emergency response planning.

**Keywords:** water security; electromagnetic pulse; cyberattack; pandemic; global catastrophic risk; catastrophic infrastructure loss; existential risk

1. # **Introduction**

International efforts to improve water access have made significant strides, with over 2 billion people gaining safely managed drinking water since 2000 [(WHO and UNICEF, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VvXsoP). Yet these advancements are threatened by global catastrophes that could swiftly reverse decades of progress. If critical infrastructure collapses, how many people would retain access to safe drinking water?

Several global catastrophic risks (GCRs) threaten widespread failure of electronics and electrical grids, via both natural or anthropogenic causes. Physical hardware damage from electromagnetic pulse (EMP) attacks [(Blouin et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Q06enY), geomagnetic storms [(Cooper and Sovacool, 2011\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?56maUU), cyberattacks causing digital or physical destruction [(Sharikov, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?S4qKxL), or high labor shortages due to extreme pandemics [(Denkenberger et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?W9OPjo) could each result in a prolonged shutdown of the majority of industries and machinery. This scenario of catastrophic infrastructure loss (CIL) would involve significant disruptions to electricity generation and distribution.

Among the most critical challenges in a CIL scenario would be ensuring access to drinking water, as modern water transport and treatment systems are heavily dependent on electricity and electronic controls. The collapse of these systems could leave billions without reliable access to water, exacerbating the risks posed by the broader infrastructural failures [(Stockton and EIS Council, 2016\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Ov1wWb). Crucially, in these extreme scenarios, affected areas — whether individual countries or entire continents — would likely need to manage without external aid, as the widespread nature of the crisis could overwhelm international response capabilities.

This is not merely a theoretical concern; the UK government in their National Risk Register estimates a 5–25% likelihood of a nuclear conflict occurring within the next five years [(UK Cabinet Office, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4eIjle). If this conflict involves high-altitude detonations, the US Congressional EMP commission estimates that the resulting EMP event could last a year or longer, resulting in long-term disruptions of water, communications, transportation, sanitation, and food systems [(Foster et al., 2008\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?lkHRTA). Such a scenario is akin to returning the affected population to pre-industrial conditions for an extended period, raising significant concerns about meeting basic needs.

1. ## **Research Needs**

While previous work has explored the impact of CIL on food security, with projected staple crop losses of 35–48% [(Moersdorf et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sKYwTS) and most countries losing at least 25–50% of their food imports [(Jehn et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2NR6Qf), little has been done on drinking/personal?/drinking and santitation water access [(Abdelkhaliq et al., 2016; Lamilla Cuellar et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?fNcjHs). Existing response plans often focus on short-term water supply and limited affected population sizes. For instance, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)’s plans only consider outages up to 21 days. Recognizing these limitations, there have been calls for innovative approaches to water disasters affecting large populations [(US EPA, 2011\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Ix0FAB), as well as further research into supply and distribution when water infrastructure fails [(Nekooie et al., 2022; van Thienen et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?q3HRnL). 

Historically, walking, cycling, and other forms of human-powered transport have been an important way to access water in disaster response, setting a precedent for considering them while assessing risks  The impact of walking, cycling, and other forms of human-powered transport emerges as a key consideration in profiling access, with a proven history of relevance in disaster response [(Babin, 2020; de Jong, 2017; Kaufman et al., 2012; Rachel, 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?IZ6ewR). Notable examples include bicycles being used for water distribution following Hurricane Sandy [(Kaufman et al., 2012\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gXMTj4), water-shuttling between resource-scarce parts of India [(Hans et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?tCqHjV), cargo bicycles being evaluated to transport supplies in Oregon during disasters [(Kirkpatrick, 2019; Page, 2014\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?buDKjF), and pushcarts being loaded with jugs to fetch water in response to infrastructure failure in Venezuela [(Hernández, 2019\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2RrDjz). However, key questions remain unanswered regarding the number of people who would lose water access in a global catastrophe, and how their needs could be met in the immediate aftermath.

Here, we build on previous studies of water access and disaster preparedness to analyze risks to water security in a CIL scenario. Our main aim is to quantify populations left without water access following infrastructure collapse and provide actionable insights for preparedness planning. By integrating data on surface water availability, population distribution, walking and cycling, and current water infrastructure into a global Monte Carlo analysis of freshwater access, we generate spatial risk profiles at continental, country, district, and high-resolution zonal (5 arcminute grid cell) levels. In order to account for high-uncertainty variables, we repeat this analysis across 1000 Monte Carlo simulations while varying walking energy expenditure, cycling power output, hours collecting water, rolling resistance, and Euclidean detour index. Additionally, we explore a case study of the ongoing water crisis in Venezuela, examining the real-world implications of our findings on water access in CIL-like conditions. This novel approach provides the first global-scale risk assessment of water access in CIL scenarios, offering critical insights to enhance resilience against extreme catastrophes. Our findings inform preparedness strategies that could potentially mitigate the risk of widespread loss of life in the event of large-scale infrastructure failure.

2. ## **Pathways to Catastrophic Infrastructure Loss**

Several key physical pathways could lead to CIL, each posing significant threats to water infrastructure and access. Among these, high-altitude electromagnetic pulse (HEMP) events present the most severe risk due to their extensive impact and prolonged recovery times [(Blouin et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sWRV1P). Caused by nuclear detonations in the upper atmosphere, HEMP events can produce near-instantaneous electromagnetic pulses capable of damaging unshielded electronics over vast areas. A single detonation could affect a region over 4000 km in diameter, comparable to the size of Western Europe or the USA [(Wilson, 2008\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6Q5etj). While less severe, extreme geomagnetic storms pose a similar threat. A high-intensity storm could disable extra high voltage transformers and trip safety switches globally, potentially leading to cascading failures in power grids [(Cooper and Sovacool, 2011\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ALPPaK). Coordinated cyberattacks — another rising concern [(Hazell, 2023; Sharikov, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?slZAPu) — could target critical control systems [(Stockton and EIS Council, 2016\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6IVPKA) to trigger CIL, possibly utilizing multiple 'Stuxnet'-like worms [(Falliere et al., 2011\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?IPP17H). These risks may grow with advancements in artificial intelligence [(Sharikov, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?t7T9Bg) and the increasing interconnectedness of electronic systems [(Krause et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?U68wjI), highlighting the vulnerabilities of interdependent water and electricity systems.

Beyond these physical risks, extreme pandemics present a distinct pathway to systemic collapse via widespread absenteeism [(Denkenberger et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?bw2M6x). Highly transmissible and pathogenic viruses could make vital workers unable or unwilling to fulfill their roles due to illness, death, or fears stemming from insufficient protection. Such labor shortages, particularly in the electricity sector, could result in widespread power outages and water infrastructure collapse. Countries were underprepared for the COVID-19 pandemic, and future natural or engineered pandemics could reach far greater magnitudes [(Gopal et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?RygyEb). Continued unpreparedness underscores the need for robust emergency solutions for water system failure.

2. # **Methodology**

   1. ## **Identifying and comparing human-powered transport options for transporting water**

An initial qualitative human-powered transport comparison was carried out to determine which options would be feasible for transporting water, and by extension were most suited to use in a catastrophe. An unstructured literature review was conducted using search terms from this set to investigate examples of usage in water fetching, usage in catastrophes, and existence of robust mathematical models for global analysis of water access. There was a scarcity of data and model availability for most options except for walking and cycling. Due to this, and bicycles being a common and widely available human-powered transport option, walking and cycling were selected for use in the global analysis.

2. ## **Global analysis overview**

In order to understand water access in a CIL scenario, we created a global risk model to quantify the proportion of populations able to access water in a catastrophe (Figure 1). The primary inputs to this were non-spatial datasets, some of which required imputation, and spatial datasets, which were pre-processed in QGIS 3.36.0 [(QGIS Development Team, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?glQHDs) to manipulate the information into a single input for further analysis (see section 2.4 Data pre-processing). The main global risk Python model then used walking and cycling models to analyze how many people could walk or cycle to freshwater sources in a global CIL scenario at a 5 arcminute resolution (i.e., zonal resolution; zone-based data). This analysis was repeated 1000 times using Monte Carlo simulations to vary the highest-uncertainty model parameters. Key results are discussed in terms of the median and 90% confidence interval (CI) from these runs.

![][image3]

**Figure 1\. Overview of modeling.**

3. ## **Data**

Spatial data were obtained for population density, distance to water, boundaries, road networks, topography, and settlement levels:

* **Population density.** The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) Socioeconomic Data and Applications Center (SEDAC) Gridded Population of the World (GPW), v4, dataset was used for population density data [(NASA Socioeconomic Data and Applications Center (SEDAC), 2016\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jvTQSA). Population density estimates are provided every five years for 2000–2020 based on census data from 2005–2014, and are available at a gridded spatial resolution of 30 arcseconds (\~1 km at the equator). 2020 data were used for this analysis.

* **Distance to water.** Distances to water were obtained from published data [(Kummu et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?zZxh7t) of a global analysis of population distance to freshwater bodies by Kummu et al. [(2011)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?oP2oRA). These data contain euclidean distances from each grid cell to the nearest surface freshwater source at a resolution of 5 arcminutes.

* **Boundaries (countries & districts).** A global geoJSON of administrative boundaries was sourced from geoBoundaries [(Runfola et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gxodWq). Administrative Level 0 (ADM0) data refer to country boundaries. Administrative Level 1 (ADM1) data define the first level of subnational divisions within a country after the country boundaries (ADM0). We refer to these solely as “districts” for consistency throughout our study, though the true naming of these subdivisions varies by country. For example, in Singapore, ADM1 refers to districts such as Central Singapore; in Australia, ADM1 refers to states such as Victoria; and in Ireland, ADM1 refers to provinces such as Munster. 

* **Road networks.** The Global Roads Inventory Project (GRIP) dataset details global roads infrastructure, categorizing roads into highway, primary, secondary, tertiary, or local roads. We utilized the summary road density data set at a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes [(Meijer et al., 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?1OM0l4). 

* **Topography.** Slope data were obtained from the EarthEnv project Topography dataset, which contains detailed environmental variables at a 10 km resolution [(Amatulli et al., 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?EX3LdF).

* **Settlement.** The Global Human Settlement Layer (GHSL) provides data on degree of urbanization using the settlement approach at a 1 km resolution, which was used to categorize grid cells as urban or rural [(Schiavina et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?JuaqBp).

Non-spatial data were used for water access and bicycle ownership levels:

* **Population counts.** Country-level population counts from 2021 were sourced from the Our World in Data “Population Growth” collection [(Ritchie et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?zol8ms), which is based on the United Nations 2022 Revision of World Population Prospects [(United Nations, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?cT7RP6).

* **Water access.** The WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (JMP) Households dataset was used to acquire percentages of households with access to piped and unpiped drinking water sources at the country level [(WHO and UNICEF, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Os54t2). “Improved” refers to sources with the ability to provide safe drinking water, including piped taps and public standposts, and unpiped boreholes, wells, rainwater, packaged water, and delivered water. For the purposes of this study, “piped” refers to tap water supply into a dwelling or plot of land, whereas “unpiped” or “nonpiped” refers to all other sources (Figure 2). JMP data are primarily sourced from household surveys and censuses, with additional input from administrative data. JMP data is disaggregated into rural and urban classified by the settlement approach — consistent with the approach of the spatial GHSL data.

* **Additional parameters.** This input refers to assumptions that feed into the model, such as the number of hours spent fetching water, whether water sources are uphill or downhill from households, and coefficients of rolling resistance for cycling on different road types. A full description of the sources for these parameters is available in the supplementary materials (Table S1).

* **Bicycle ownership.** Percentages of household bicycle ownership per country were sourced from Oke et al. [(2015)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?uJ6kGX).

![][image4]

**Figure 2: Overview of water access categories.** "PIPED" refers to water supplied to multiple households, requiring extensive external piped infrastructure. "UNPIPED" encompasses all other sources, including dug wells and tubewells, which may have some piped components but require minimal centralized infrastructure. \*Exceptions classed under “Piped water, Other”: sources listed as unpiped in the diagram will count as piped instead if they deliver water to multiple households, such as a borehole that delivers water to an overhead tank for supplying multiple households.  Adapted from WHO and UNICEF [(2018)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LMha5Z).

4. ## **Data pre-processing**

Geospatial data was pre-processed in QGIS 3.36.0 [(QGIS Development Team, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8ZUXJT). The distance to water, population density, country boundaries, district boundaries, road networks, topography, and settlement datasets were first imported into QGIS. All data were reprojected to EPSG 4326 WGS 84, and all raster data were resampled to 5 arcminutes (≈10 km at the equator). Next, a 5 arcminutes vector grid was created over the distance to water data, allowing the subsequent creation of grid centroids. This resolution was chosen for a balance between accuracy and computational load. After this, the *join by location* tool was used to join the map and points, then the *sample raster values* tool was used for each raster. These steps ensure the grid points have all data attributes, and then they can be exported for use in the global Python model.

The WHO/UNICEF JMP and bicycle ownership datasets had missing data, and were pseudo-spatially imputed to account for this. The JMP dataset had 0.5–22.1% missing values for each column, mainly for water quality data specified as rural or urban (18.3–22.1% missing) with total water quality data being more complete (0.5–1.9% missing). For the bicycle ownership dataset, 36.5% of countries had missing data. Pseudo-spatial imputation was done by using the mean value of bordering countries. If there were no data from bordering countries, then the mean of the subregion was used. If there were no subregion data, then the continent mean was used. Some missing data points were filled from national data sources rather than imputing if data was available; these are tracked in the imputation script in the codebase.

5. ## **Main global analysis model**

For the global analysis, existing peer-reviewed cycling and walking models were introduced to calculate water access (sections 2.5.1 and 2.5.2). These models required slight modifications to manage loads and slopes in a manner suitable for the purposes of this project (section 2.5.3). This model setup facilitated a sensitivity analysis to determine which variables had the highest impact on results (section 2.5.4), which were then accounted for in the final analyses. The global spatial datasets were introduced to implement these models on a worldwide basis, accounting for population density, distance to water, country and district boundaries, topography, road networks, and degree of urbanization (sections 2.5.5 and 2.5.6). 

Distances achievable were modeled using Euclidean distance coupled with a detour index which is commonly employed in testing for walking accessibility [(Páez et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?wfgG75). This method was chosen to balance accuracy with the high computational costs of global spatial analyses. National data on bicycle ownership enabled the modeling of the proportion of individuals in an area who are able to cycle to collect water. National data on current water access, disaggregated into urban and rural and coupled with geospatial urbanization data, facilitated the investigation of urban versus rural water availability. This allowed for more realistic modeling of current water access differences between urban and rural areas. The final model aggregates the proportion of populations able to access freshwater sources from a 5 arcminute resolution to the district, country, and continental level. All sources and assumptions for model parameters are available in the supplementary materials (Table S1).

1. ### *Martin cycling model*

The Martin et al. [(1998)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rnHeKZ) bicycle model is used to simulate bicycle use in collecting and transporting water under varying load, slope, and rolling resistance conditions. It has previously been shown to be accurate, with a high correlation between measured and modeled power (R2 \= .97) and low standard error (2.7 W) [(Martin et al., 1998\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?9rZIp9). The original model includes power components for aerodynamic drag (PAD) potential energy (PPE), wheel bearings (PWB), rolling resistance (PRR), kinetic energy (PKE), and drivetrain friction (PC). Power lost to wheel bearing friction is relatively small in the original study [(Martin et al., 1998\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?WzDl0d), and the kinetic energy component is expected to be small in water transport as changes in speed are assumed to be infrequent. As such, these components were excluded from our analysis, and aerodynamic wheel rotation losses were excluded from the aerodynamic drag, to simplify the model. 

Aerodynamic drag, rolling resistance, and potential energy are described below in Equations 1, 2, and 3, respectively, where ⍴ is air density, CD is the coefficient of drag, A is the frontal area (m2), vA is air velocity (m.s\-1) which was modeled as ‘no wind’ and is consequently equal to vG, the ground velocity of the bicycle and rider (m.s\-1), Crr is the coefficient of rolling resistance, mt is the total mass of the bicycle and rider (kg), g is acceleration due to gravity (m.s\-2), and sd is slope (radians).

1) PAD=12CDA va2vG  
2) PRR=vGCRRmtg  
3) PPE=vGsdmtg

Total cycling power (watts) is calculated as the sum of power lost to aerodynamic drag, rolling resistance, and potential energy, divided by a chain efficiency factor (Ec) to account for power lost to drivetrain friction (Equation 4).

4) PT=(PAD+PRR+PPE)EC

   2. ### *Lankford walking model*

The Lankford et al. [(2020)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2fBXsg) walking model is used to simulate collecting and transporting water under varying load and slope conditions. When compared to four other walking models in its capstone paper — Pandolf et al. [(1977)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?F7M9b2), Minetti et al. [(2002)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?cspEMW), American College of Sports Medicine [(Ferguson, 2014\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0EafD8), and Load Carriage Decision Aid [(Looney et al., 2019\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4RFlgr) — the Lankford model had the highest adjusted R2 value (0.89) and the lowest root mean square error (5.92 kJ/min). As such, and given its capacity for modeling variable load carrying unlike more popular simple models such as Tobler’s Hiking function [(Tobler, 1993\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?mTVyfe), it was selected as a suitably accurate walking model. Total walking metabolic cost (Cw) in VO2 (ml.kg\-1.min\-1) is calculated in Equation 5, where v is velocity (m.s\-1), and sp is slope (percentage gradient). Energy expenditure is inputted to the global model as units of Metabolic Equivalent of Task (MET) and multiplied by 3.5 to be converted to VO2 [(Jetté et al., 1990\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?OpMhvc).

5) CW=5.43483+6.47383v+(−0.05372sp) \+0.652298vsp+0.023761vsp2  
   \+0.000320vsp3

   3. ### *Managing loads and slopes*

The Martin and Lankford models both require adaptations to account for carrying load. Similarly, the Martin model requires adaptations for maximum loads and managing slopes.

* **Load carrying (walking).** The Lankford model was adjusted to accommodate a ‘total load’ which included the mass of the water load in addition to body mass. It was assumed that people would use a variety of carrying methods, including but not limited to backpacks, head carrying, or carrying poles. Given modeling torso (backpack) loads as body mass has been shown to be a reasonable approximation of the metabolic cost of carrying external loads [(Bastien et al., 2005\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?uYst7t), the sum of body mass and water mass was used to model metabolic cost. The metabolic energy budget — how much energy a person has for collecting water — was based only on body mass.   
* **Load carrying (cycling).** The mass of the load was added to the mass of the bicycle modeled using the Martin model. It was assumed that loads could be carried either attached to the rider or attached to the bicycle itself. At slow speeds, changes to aerodynamics and wind resistance caused by a different surface area profile (e.g., jerry cans strapped to a bicycle) are minimal and were therefore ignored.  
* **Maximum loads.** As bicycles have structural limits to the mass they can carry, a “rated capacity” variable was included to account for this. However, “practical limit” variables were also introduced for cycling and walking to represent the maximum loads that can realistically be carried long distances after considering stability and fatigue.  
* **Hill steepness.** In scenarios where hills become sufficiently steep, bicycles and other human-powered transport options have gearing ratios that impose a limit on how slowly they can go when hauling a heavy mass, resulting in a maximum mass beyond which a human will be unable to push the vehicle up the hill. To account for this, a maximum pushable weight constraint is added to the model. This is designed to simulate a person pushing the human-powered vehicle by hand and is defined by combining the average maximum pushing force exertion of humans with the force from the loaded human-powered transport object due to gravity on a slope.  
* **Slope polarity** Slope has a very large impact on cycling velocity, and is factored into the models. However, assumptions need to be made on whether the water source is uphill or downhill from a person. If a water source is uphill, they get to cycle the uphill portion unloaded, but if it is downhill, they have to cycle uphill with the added weight of the water. In reality, paths will be going up and down hills. The slope direction was randomly varied in model runs to account for the range of possibilities, rather than assuming solely uphill or downhill water sources. Additionally, cycling downhill with a heavy load may be unstable, but unrestricted models will not take this into account. Cycling speeds were limited to a maximum of 7 m.s\-1 (≈ 25 km.h\-1) to address this latter point. 

  4. ### *Sensitivity analysis*

A sensitivity analysis was conducted on the cycling and walking model to assess how different input variables affect the average achievable speeds across varying conditions (Figure 3). For each of the selected parameters, the value was varied between a minimum and maximum expected value to determine the impact on water ration kms, defined as the product of water carried and distance traveled. The top five parameters for cycling were water ration, coefficient of rolling resistance, time gathering water, power output, and practical (load) limit. For walking, the top five parameters were energy expenditure, water ration, human mass, time gathering water, and practical (load) limit. 

![][image5]

**Figure 3: Sensitivity analysis of mobility model parameters. a,** sensitivity analysis of Martin cycling model. **b,** sensitivity analysis of Lankford walking model. HPV \= human-powered vehicle.

If a variable had a large impact on the model results, improved data sources were obtained to reduce uncertainty bounds, or it was flagged as a variable for Monte Carlo simulations. The top five variables for each model were deemed significant enough to investigate further. After reviewing emergency water standards, 15 L/person/day was set as a fixed water ration due to being a common recommendation for catastrophes [(Luff and Clarke, 2006; Sphere Association, 2018; UNHCR, 2020; Wisner et al., 2002\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4hRo8A). While varying practical load limits were enforced for cycling and walking, the 15 L water ration was always within these bounds. Country-specific averages were introduced for human mass, in order to reduce variation in the simulations. The variation in coefficient of rolling resistance was reduced by mapping rolling resistance values to the dominant road type of each GIS grid cell [(Meijer et al., 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?oIwKnn). However, it was still added to the Monte Carlo analysis, as the path to water may not follow the most common road type in the area. Walking energy expenditure, cycling power output, and hours spent collecting water were also added to the Monte Carlo analysis.

5. ### *Implementing mobility models at the global scale*

The Martin and Lankford models were iterated over each grid cell of the world dataset in Python 3.9.19. Following the GIS processing described in 2.3 Data Processing, each grid centroid has data on population density, distance to water, slope, dominant road type, and degree of urbanization. For the mobility models, distance can be combined with time allocated to gathering water to produce velocity, grid cell slope provides slope, and dominant road type provides a coefficient of rolling resistance for cycling. Using the GRIP dataset [(Meijer et al., 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?iHArbr), Crr values for road surfaces were mapped to the most common road type in each grid cell to provide a Crr for each model run. Combining these data allows for the Martin and Lankford models to be run on every grid cell across the globe.

In order to calculate water access, data on population counts, piped water availability, and bicycle ownership were used. For walking access to water sources, population counts were used to weigh the population density in a grid cell, with all of the population in a cell either having access or not having access (because each 10x10 km cell has a single value of distance to water, slope, and dominant road type). However, if a proportion of the population in a given cell relies on unpiped water, it was assumed that they could still access water. Data on urbanization using a settlement approach to define rurality [(Schiavina et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?iVbogD) categorized grid cells as either rural or urban. National rural or urban piped water percentages [(WHO and UNICEF, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0ZoTUu) were used to calculate the proportion of populations relying on piped or non-piped sources for each cell. The population able to access water by cycling was weighted by national bicycle ownership levels (e.g., if an Australian grid cell is not within walking distance from water but is within cycling distance, and household bicycle ownership levels for Australia are 60%, only 60% of people will be able to access it by cycling).

6. ### *Monte Carlo simulations*

The concurrent.futures inbuilt Python module (Python 3.9.19) was used to run 1000 simulations of the global model analysis, varying key parameters identified in the sensitivity analysis. Time gathering water was sampled as a normal distribution between 4 and 7 hours, human power output for cycling between 20 and 80 W, and human energy expenditure for walking between 3 and 6 METs. Coefficient of rolling resistance was adjusted between one road type better or one road type worse than the dominant road type in the area, sampled randomly between \[-1, 0, 1\]. For example, a grid cell with local roads as the dominant road type would vary randomly between the coefficients of rolling resistance for no roads, local roads, and tertiary roads. This process was bounded, meaning coefficients of rolling resistance could not drop below the value for the best road type (highways) or rise above the value for the worst road type (no roads). Euclidean distance detour index for urban cells was sampled as a normal distribution between 1.2 and 1.5 [(Boyacı et al., 2021; Chen and Chen, 2021; Morita et al., 2014\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gjssSa), and for rural cells with a Pareto distribution between 1 and 2.5 [(Carling et al., 2012; Jeon et al., 2017; Páez et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jANlSL).

7. ### *Visualization of spatial data*

Final model results were reprojected to Winkel tripel projection for visualization in QGIS 3.36.0 [(QGIS Development Team, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Oaxf7C). Identical color scales were used for the maps of the world and Venezuela. 

3. # **Results and discussion**

   1. ## **Global populations at risk of insufficient water access**

Our model results indicate that 24.3% (90% CI 14.4-34.8%) of the world's population — approximately 1.9 billion people — would be unable to access sufficient water in the aftermath of a global CIL scenario (Figure 4). At the continent level, our model reveals significant variability in the proportion of populations potentially losing water access (Figure 4b). The Americas show the highest vulnerability, with 39.2% (90% CI 24.6–54.2%) of the population at risk of losing water access. Europe follows with 24.6% (90% CI 10.7–42.3%), then Africa at 22.7% (90% CI 15.3–30.0%), Asia at 21.3% (90% CI 12.2–31.5%), and Oceania at 18.8% (90% CI 9.0–32.2%). These results indicate that all regions, including those traditionally considered water-secure, face substantial risks in a loss of infrastructure scenario. 

**![][image6]**

**Figure 4\. Global and continental distribution of water access following infrastructure collapse. a,** Distribution of Monte Carlo results for population without water after infrastructure collapse. **b,** breakdown of median results for population with and without water. As medians are provided for the walking and cycling sub-models, results will be slightly different from the simulation results for the main model (no access/access). As such, “undefined access” covers people that would have access, but whether this is walking or cycling access is undefined (\<= 2%).

The breakdown of access modes also varies substantially between continents (Figure 4b). Bicycles would enable 12.0% of the global population — approximately 1 billion people — to access water sources beyond walking range. However, cycling is proportionally more useful in Europe and the Americas, with 19.1% and 18.1% of people reaching water by bicycle, whereas only 2.9% of people in Africa could cycle to water. In contrast, many people in Africa (60.4%) — along with Asia (38.5%) and Oceania (23.3%) — only maintain access in CIL due to relying on modeled unpiped sources. While unpiped water should remain accessible in CIL events in theory, it is important to note that real-world outcomes may differ due to factors not captured in our analysis. Therefore, these results should be interpreted as indicators of potential risk levels rather than precise predictions.

When considering total numbers rather than proportions, the results show a significant concentration of impact in Asia (Figure 5a). China and India alone would see 560 million people losing water access. Driven by the large populations in Asia, these results show that despite the better proportional performance of the region, a catastrophic loss of infrastructure scenario in Asia would result in an unprecedented water loss crisis, dwarfing those in other regions.

**![][image7]Figure 5: Median populations without water access in a global CIL scenario. a,** Number of people losing water access after CIL, plotted at a 5 arc-minute resolution. **b,** Proportion of population losing water access after CIL per district. Populations are deemed to be without water access if they normally rely on piped water, cannot walk to water and back, and cannot cycle to water and back. Median results are displayed from 1000 Monte Carlo simulations.

In these scenarios, external humanitarian assistance is assumed to be unavailable, leaving localized governance structures and informal networks as the primary response mechanisms for affected regions (Figure 5b). Districts with lower proportions of populations without water are likely to have greater capacity to assist their constituents, including through national aid and the establishment of water-sharing networks between those with and without access. In contrast, districts with higher proportions of affected populations may face significant challenges in self-sufficiency and aid provision, as residents struggle to meet basic needs and water-sharing becomes infeasible due to widespread scarcity and conflict [(Gleick and Shimabuku, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?mAhcwQ). In these high-risk areas, populations may be forced to relocate in search of resources, potentially overwhelming neighboring districts. This district-level analysis, combined with the zonal analysis, offers national governments a valuable tool for initial risk assessments, especially in larger countries with numerous districts. It provides a starting point for identifying at-risk localities, understanding how governance structures may be impacted, and prioritizing areas where cooperative water management strategies are least likely to emerge spontaneously, thus requiring more immediate intervention.

In our model, the median one-way distance people were capable of travelling was up to 3.6 km (90% CI: 1.6–6.1 km) for walking and 11.8 km (90% CI: 6.7–16.6 km) for cycling globally — comparable to existing practices in regions without piped infrastructure. In these areas, one-way walking trips of 3–5 km are typical in Asia and Africa [(OHCHR et al., 2010\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5lXkON), with distances of over 5 km documented in Morocco, Uganda, and South Africa [(South African Department of Rural Development and Land Reform, 2012; UN Development Programme, 2012\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?EMTsjX). These distances likely represent upper limits for populations accustomed to piped water, given that a third of adults worldwide do not meet minimum physical activity levels [(Strain et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rhWsmv) and lack experience with water fetching. Data on cycling for water-fetching is scarce, but European [(Solheim and Stangeby, 1997\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?w1rtOX) and Canadian [(Larsen et al., 2010\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?W5mbQw) studies suggest that acceptable distances for cycling are typically three times greater than for walking — relatively close to our median factor of 3.3. Overall, the general correspondence between modeled and observed water-collection practices provides a baseline validation of our post-catastrophe accessibility estimates.

2. ## **Lessons from the Venezuelan water crisis**

Venezuela’s decade-long energy crisis vividly demonstrates how large-scale electricity loss can destabilize water access for populations reliant on piped sources. Corruption, poor system maintenance, brain drain, and a lack of adequate backups have contributed to nationwide blackouts over the last decade, accompanied by mass water insecurity and regular shortages [(Jones, 2019; McMillan, 2021; Rendon et al., 2019\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?DmmMG4). When piped water stopped completely in major cities for over four days in 2019, residents were forced to gather contaminated water from drain pipes and rivers as the sheer size of the shortages overwhelmed the capability of water trucks and other contingency plans [(Rojas, 2019\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?GrWq3f). Even with some infrastructure and emergency response systems available, this partial collapse of water systems has contributed to surges in infectious disease outbreaks, spikes in infant and maternal mortality, educational facility closures, and millions fleeing the country [(Rendon et al., 2019\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?yBwPk1). The impacts of full infrastructure collapse would be unprecedented. 

Our results put Venezuela at high risk, with 48.0% (90% CI 33.9–59.4%) of the nation unable to access a freshwater source in a full CIL scenario (Figure 6). The densely-populated coastal regions would be some of the worst affected in terms of absolute and relative numbers affected, with 85.1% of the capital district and 66.5% of La Guaira unable to reach freshwater. However, even inland districts such as Táchira could be expected to see hundreds of thousands without access. In the worst affected city of the current crisis, Punto Fijo, Falcón, 31% of residents reportedly received no water from their pipes [(OVSP, 2020a)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5jPhAB). CIL, in contrast, would see up to the entire 78% of Venezuela’s piped water population losing their supply. Many of the current alternatives — storing intermittent water, paying water trucks, sourcing water from other locations, and buying bottled water — would be severely impacted by the CIL for the 98% of Venezuelans who rely on these to some degree [(OVSP, 2020b)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?3FYulX). Without functioning infrastructure, the availability of fuel to power water trucks or intermittent service to allow storage becomes far less likely.

![][image8]

**Figure 6: Populations without water access in Venezuela in a CIL scenario. a,** Proportion of population losing water access after CIL per district. **b,** Number of people losing water access after CIL, plotted at a 5 arc-minute resolution. Populations are deemed to be without water access if they normally rely on piped water, cannot walk to water and back, and cannot cycle to water and back. Median results are displayed from 1000 Monte Carlo simulations. Pop. \= population.	

The Venezuelan response to the current humanitarian crisis underscores both the importance of risk-profiling water access and the need for fair governance. To meet basic needs during shortages at an individual level, some have made use of bucket-laden dollies, pushcarts, and bicycles to fetch water [(Hernández, 2019; Smith et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?htcQ4D), while others have built rudimentary water systems by connecting pipes from distant sources to homes in the city [(Smith et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5ZKzWT). At the institutional level, the Venezuelan Observatory of Public Services regularly monitored access to piped water infrastructure, how often water is actually received, and how far people have to travel to obtain water [(OVSP, 2020b)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vGi8LD). However, its website and communication channels have been down since August 2024, potentially related to the passing of an “anti-NGO” law the same month [(Amnesty International, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rXscaR). In light of this, response planning for CIL should make sure to carefully consider how to build preparedness systems at the individual, institutional, and government levels that will remain functional, just, and equitable throughout severe crises.

3. ##  **Solutions and next steps**

Electrical and water systems remain critically vulnerable to the events described here. With relatively little funding dedicated to CIL preparedness [(Stockton and EIS Council, 2016\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?mCsHb2), this lack of preparation leaves an opportunity for targeted, high-impact actions. Though preventing CIL scenarios and developing resilient infrastructure would be an ideal first line of defense HERE, distributed generation and microgrids are currently far from ubiquitous [(Denkenberger et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BUFSiT) and hardening the U.S. electrical grid alone against HEMP has been estimated at \~$20 billion [(Pry, 2014\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?CgtcDr). In the absence of such interventions, lower-cost contingency measures against these risks such as rapid response plans have been estimated to be a cost-effective way of saving lives [(Denkenberger et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ROJvN5). We highlight three key domains to address in this area: risk assessment, research and development, and societal readiness.

1. ### *Risk Assessment*

Fundamental to developing preparedness and resilience to risks to water access is conducting place based risk assessments which incorporate local knowledge, vulnerabilities, and conditions. For this global analysis, ADM1 districts have been used as proxies for governance units. Recognizing the limitations of fixed administrative boundaries, particularly in capturing local community dynamics such as social cohesion, geographical proximity, and informal support networks, we also provide more granular zone-level data[^1]. This enables local agencies and researchers to create custom groupings beyond the district level, tailoring analyses to specific geographical, social, or governance contexts. Utilizing this zone-level data allows for the investigation of potential pinch points in water access, assessment of cascading relocation risks, and incorporation of detailed local knowledge too specific for our global scope. 

Responsible government agencies, multinational non governmental bodies, and intergovernmental organizations should incorporate these tailored analyses into all-hazard risk assessments which include catastrophic risks to fill this current gap in the landscape. In this manner, water access in CIL events could be integrated into existing frameworks such as the Indian National Disaster Management Authority Guidelines [(NMDA, 2007\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?zW2tQN), the US EPA’s Roadmap to a Secure and Resilient Water and Wastewater Sector [(Adams et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?mxlU0y), or the EU Directive on the Resilience of Critical Entities [(European Commission, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?92qBfB). This can allow response teams to preemptively assess which areas are most likely to be endangered. In doing so, the effectiveness of targeted interventions such as water trucks, relocation assistance, and cooperative water management strategies can be maximized.

2. ### *Research & development*

One way countries can strengthen their ability to respond to CIL is by researching and setting up back-up systems for water supply networks. Germany, for example, has plans in place to connect mobile pipes from water networks that are still functioning to those that have failed in a disaster, or to activate its network of over 5,200 decentralized emergency groundwater wells in severe crises [(Stallkamp et al., 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?XzHoHe). Similarly, researchers in Poland have proposed methods to drain a few days’ worth of accumulated water from supply networks if they fail [(Szpak and Szczepanek, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?tP2Ty2). However, this level of preparation appears uncommon. Governments can therefore increase resilience by developing technological solutions like these, as well as by providing water utilities with (unplugged) backup generators, fuel supplies, and emergency communication systems [(Stockton and EIS Council, 2016\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Yi4axZ).

In terms of lower-resource options, countries and other response groups can provide stepwise guidance on implementing emergency water systems specifically tailored for CIL, matching the precedent set by humanitarian water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) guides for current crises (e.g., [(Luff and Clarke, 2006; Oxfam, 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Tg5crH)). Surface water access as presented here is a start, but further research is required to assess which alternative strategies are suitable for different locations: rainwater can improve water security in many regions dependent on seasonality [(Musayev et al., 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?f45NWv), residential hot water tanks typically have about 110–190 L of water that can be used for drinking in emergencies [(County of Alameda, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?YY28p6), groundwater could be accessed manually from protected wells using buckets, shallow scoops in ephemeral streams can yield potable water in apparently dry conditions, solar stills can distill saltwater, radiative air wells can passively collect nighttime condensation [(Wutich et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0N3cdo), and emergency gravity-fed piped water systems can transport water over long distances [(Smith et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VLcsBS). Follow-on work should also analyze which treatment options can be rapidly scaled in different countries and districts. Eight million tonnes of liquid chlorine are produced annually [(Chemanalyst, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?TLpHad), potentially providing an enormous reservoir for treatment. Investigating the emergency-use potential of disinfection, boiling, filtration, coagulation, flocculation, sedimentation, and solar disinfection options can inform response guides to ensure water safety is adequately considered and planned for.

While these interventions may provide a short-term fix, future work should also consider how to ensure more sustainable long-term water access after CIL. Emergency rations of 15 L are the minimum needed in a disaster, but 50 L or more may be needed afterwards to maintain sanitation, health, and dignity [(Sphere Association, 2018; UNHCR, 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0qMFGY) with pandemic scenarios demanding even higher volumes for enhanced hygiene practices [(Antwi et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LClpGn). Water distribution in current humanitarian crises is reliant on functioning infrastructure through systems such as water trucking and packaged water [(Sikder et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?XMpNBr), however fossil fuel shortages will limit trucking abilities in the short term. Vehicles retrofitted for alternative fuels such as wood gasification may help address this [(Nelson et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?DGuPDE), but the logistics of mass water trucking remain underexplored. Alternatively, alternative fuels such as wood gasification may be able to provide electricity for water supply systems [(Williams et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?nl2LVz).

3. ### *Societal Readiness*

In a CIL scenario, protecting high-risk households — those farthest from water sources or composed of individuals with disabilities, the elderly, or others unable to gather water — will be crucial for ensuring an effective and equitable response. Following Hurricane María in Puerto Rico, 85% of households participated in water sharing networks, which spontaneously emerged in the wake of a disaster, and assisted all households including those at high-risk [(Roque et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?QkJhAc). In a systematic review, Bradley et al. [(2014)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Co2uR4) found information campaigns can be an effective strategy at increasing the knowledge and readiness of the public in disaster scenarios. These methods are currently used by governments, as evidenced by Sweden, Finland, and Germany recently distributing emergency response guides including guidance on water shortages in crises and wartime [(Henley et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZYXBTx), setting a precedent for CIL-tailored recommendations. Once place-based risk assessments have been completed, impactful activities identified, such as the promotion of water sharing networks, can be communicated to communities to improve preparedness. If communication systems are down, this may require satellite phones and backup shortwave radio networks.

If implemented carefully, both societal and government-level readiness initiatives have the potential to reduce the risk of conflict — an outcome often driven by water scarcity. A total of 1,298 water-related conflicts have been documented between 2400 BCE and early 2022 [(Gleick and Shimabuku, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?SfkPsT). Access to fresh drinking water is often limited for poorer households [(Yang et al., 2013\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Y8nUFK) but effective management practices can enhance water availability even in less affluent regions [(Krueger et al., 2019\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0lLEsS). While inclusive, cooperative water management strategies have been shown to mitigate conflict [(de Castro-Pardo et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?XxnBcl), ex-post implementation will be incredibly difficult. It is therefore crucial to explicitly consider the risks of water-related conflict in CIL planning to ensure continuous and equitable access.

4. ### *Limitations* 

The analysis we present here has several limitations. Regarding the modeling itself, our work does not consider rainwater collection, groundwater access potential, potability, or human-powered transport options beyond walking and cycling. Future studies could add these components to build upon our methodology and generate more robust results. Moreover, we extrapolate bicycle ownership and piped water rates from national sources and use Euclidean distances with detour indexes to approximate travel routes in place of more precise but computationally expensive alternatives (e.g., AccessMod [(Ray and Ebener, 2008\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gDuHzA)). Similarly, we assume all piped populations lose access and all non-piped populations maintain access, despite some cities such as Vienna having gravity-fed systems that should still function without electricity [(Plan et al., 2010\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?aExoRq) and some non-piped users relying on trucked water [(Lane and Kumpel, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?w4z2Lp) or electricity-powered wells. While we believe these are reasonable assumptions for a global scale analysis, we especially recommend that country- and below level analyses used for planning should reduce reliance on them, particularly if better datasets are locally available. 

As this study focuses on the loss of piped water, the results are best viewed as net change from current-day water access. Many water-insecure countries with minimal piped water infrastructure performed well in our results, such as South Sudan. This should not be interpreted as being water-secure following CIL, but as having a smaller relative change in access. An average of 21.8% of households in water-insecure regions of low- and middle-income countries already consider moving due to water-related issues, as high as 66.8% in San Borja, Bolivia [(Stoler et al., 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UsBBqV). In the event of CIL, factors such as reduced treatment options, reduced water trucking, and price spikes from water vendors could be the tipping point in being able to access water locally for already-vulnerable populations. Strengthening today’s water infrastructure and expanding universal access (as targeted by the UN’s Sustainable Development Goal 6\) can reduce ongoing suffering while also improving preparedness for catastrophic risks in the future.

4. #  **Conclusion**

Populations are at risk of severe water insecurity in the event of catastrophic infrastructure loss (CIL), immediately threatening the survival of nearly a third of the world in a global-scale event. However, adequate planning to identify alternative water sources and retrieval methods if piped infrastructure fails could mitigate the impacts of such catastrophes and increase societal resilience. While we provide an initial model to inform this planning, future research can build upon this by tackling some of its limitations. Combining freshwater access with consideration of non-freshwater sources, non-piped population needs, and water quality would allow for more robust findings to aid response planning. Governments should use the results of these studies, factoring in local knowledge and requirements, to conduct risk analyses for water access in CIL that feed directly into establishing contingency plans. In this manner, preparing low-cost measures to identify those most at risk, provide location-tailored guidance on emergency access and treatment options, and promote cooperative water management strategies has the potential to decrease the impact and inequity of water loss should a CIL event occur.
